title: Draymond Green makes NBA history with unique triple-double vs. Grizzlies
text:
February 10, 2017 11:40pm EST February 10, 2017 11:40pm EST Green's accomplishment certainly impacts like a roundhouse kick, regardless. (Getty Images) 
Updated at 11:40 p.m. ET 
Updated at 11:40 p.m. ET 
Draymond Green accomplished a feet (oops) feat, that no other player in NBA history has done. 
On Friday vs. the Grizzlies, the Warriors forward recorded a triple-double — without scoring 10 points. It's the first of its kind in NBA history. And it's OK Green didn't score much, because the Warriors had no problem putting up points on Memphis: They hung a 122 spot on the Grizzlies in Memphis. 
Green's final line: 12 rebounds, 10 assists and 10 steals. He also put up four points on six shots from the floor. #DraymondGreen : 12 REB, 10 AST, & 10 STL. The 1st player EVER with a triple-double without 10+ PTS! Here's how the 2-Time All-Star did it: pic.twitter.com/MYAlQ5THHt — NBA (@NBA) February 11, 2017 
While Green came up six points shy of the quadruple-double, his accomplishment regardless impacts like a roundhouse kick. 
Green's performance helped the Dubs to their 45th win on the season, keeping them firmly in first place in the Western Conference. Watch This
